  "market_context": "NQ on 5-minute time frame after sweeping the previous day high, with expansion met by opposing expansion forming a reversal wick on the 6 AM 4-hour candle. Bias is bearish, and the analyst is looking to align the lower time frame fractal model with the higher time frame reversal.",
  "key_observation": "The 6 AM 4-hour candle formed a reversal with a large opposing wick, while the 5-minute and hourly fractal model printed a T-spot, signalling that 10 AM should deliver the candle 3 continuation expansion lower with a shallow wick.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identified that price swept the previous day high on the NQ 5-minute chart, with expansion met by expansion forming a reversal.",
    "Confirmed the higher time frame context: the 6 AM 4-hour candle printed a reversal wick, projecting the 10 AM 4-hour candle as the candle 3 continuation lower.",
    "Dropped to the 5-minute and hourly fractal model and observed the T-spot being printed, defining where the wick should form before expansion.",
    "Defined invalidation: price should not trade above the opposing candle / into the fair value gap above the T-spot, so stop loss is placed on the opposing candle or fair value gap.",
    "Selected target as -1 standard deviation rather than deeper deviations, because the large opposing run made deeper projections unrealistic relative to the range.",
    "Took the entry within the wick zone aligned with the hourly model and managed for at least 2R."
  ],
  "outcome": "Target hit at -1 standard deviation; price opened, made a shallow high, then expanded lower into the target.",
  "lessons": "When higher time frame reversal candles have large opposing wicks, scale target expectations down (e.g., -1 standard deviation) and align the lower time frame fractal T-spot for precision entry with invalidation on the opposing candle.",
